  "texts": [
    "Conversely, it may prolong construction timelines due to delayed setting and hardening and may require additional curing to ensure adequate strength development.",
    "The impact of delayed heat of hydration depends on the specific application and project requirements [30].3 Types of supplementary materials SFSF, a by-product of silicon alloy production, is increasingly recognized as a valuable SCM in concrete applications.",
    "This material is formed during the volatilization of silica in submerged electric furnaces, where vapors condense at temperatures exceeding 2000°C, transforming quartz into silicon [31].",
    "Commonly referred to as silica dust or micro-silica, SF typically appears in grey or white, with the latter color often signifying higher quality.",
    "A key characteristic of SF is its extremely fine particle size, measuring less than 0.00004 inches, which significantly enhances its effectiveness in concrete [32]."
  ]
}